Scotland &#91;e&#93; is a [country](/Countries_of_the_United_Kingdom) that constitutes part of the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom). It occupies nearly a third of the land area of the UK, comprising the northern portion of the island of [Great Britain](/Great_Britain) and an archipelago of over 790 adjacent [islands](/Islands_of_Scotland), primarily concentrated in the [Hebrides](/Hebrides) and the [Northern Isles](/Northern_Isles). As of 2022, the country's population was tallied at approximately 5.4 million souls, a fact they are occasionally reminded of. &#91;11&#93; Its capital city is [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh), a place of dramatic hills and even more dramatic rents, while [Glasgow](/Glasgow) holds the title of largest city and is the most populous of the [cities of Scotland](/Cities_of_Scotland). To the south-east, Scotland shares its [solitary land border](/Anglo-Scottish_border) with [England](/England), a stretch of 96 miles (154 km) that has seen more history than is probably healthy. The country is otherwise surrounded by water: the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) to the north and west, the [North Sea](/North_Sea) to the north-east and east, and the [Irish Sea](/Irish_Sea) to the south.

Its legislature, the [Scottish Parliament](/Scottish_Parliament), elects 129 [members](/Member_of_the_Scottish_Parliament) to represent 73 [constituencies](/List_of_Scottish_Parliament_constituencies_and_electoral_regions_(2011%E2%80%932026)) across the nation, a democratic exercise in managing expectations. &#91;12&#93; The [Scottish Government](/Scottish_Government) serves as the [executive arm](/Executive_(government)) of this devolved government, led by the [first minister](/First_Minister_of_Scotland), who presides over the [cabinet](/Scottish_Cabinet) and is tasked with formulating government policy and handling [international engagement](/International_relations_of_Scotland), which is as complex as it sounds. &#91;13&#93; &#91;14&#93;

The [Kingdom of Scotland](/Kingdom_of_Scotland) materialized as an independent [sovereign state](/Sovereign_state) in the 9th century, a time of considerable political upheaval and questionable haircuts. In a pivotal moment of dynastic convenience, [James VI](/James_VI) of Scotland inherited the thrones of the [Kingdom of England](/Kingdom_of_England) and the [Kingdom of Ireland](/Kingdom_of_Ireland) in 1603, creating a [personal union](/Personal_union) of the [three kingdoms](/Union_of_the_Crowns). On 1 May 1707, Scotland and England formally merged to establish the new [Kingdom of Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain), &#91;15&#93; &#91;16&#93; an arrangement that saw the [Parliament of Scotland](/Parliament_of_Scotland) absorbed into the [Parliament of Great Britain](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain). Fast forward to 1999, and a [Scottish Parliament](/Scottish_Parliament) was re-established, now holding [devolved](/Devolution) authority over a wide range of [domestic policy](/Domestic_policy) areas. &#91;17&#93; The nation retains its own unique [legal system](/Scots_law), [education system](/Education_in_Scotland), and [religious history](/History_of_Christianity_in_Scotland), all of which have stubbornly contributed to the persistence of [Scottish culture](/Culture_of_Scotland) and a distinct [national identity](/Scottish_national_identity). &#91;18&#93;

In terms of [languages spoken in the country](/Languages_of_Scotland), [Scottish English](/Scottish_English) and [Scots](/Scots_language) are the most prevalent, existing on a [dialect continuum](/Dialect_continuum) that ranges from mutually intelligible to bewildering. &#91;19&#93; [Scottish Gaelic](/Scottish_Gaelic) speakers are scattered across Scotland, but the language is primarily spoken as a native tongue in communities within the [Hebrides](/Hebrides). &#91;20&#93; Despite Gaelic speakers now comprising less than 2% of the total population, state-sponsored [revitalisation](/Revitalisation_of_Scottish_Gaelic) efforts have cultivated a growing community of [second language](/Second_language) speakers, proving that some things refuse to go quietly. &#91;21&#93;

The mainland of Scotland is conventionally divided into three regions: the [Highlands](/Scottish_Highlands), a formidable mountainous area in the north and north-west; the [Lowlands](/Scottish_Lowlands), a comparatively flat plain slicing through the country's center; and the [Southern Uplands](/Southern_Uplands), a region of rolling hills along the southern border. The Highlands are the most mountainous part of the British Isles and host its highest peak, [Ben Nevis](/Ben_Nevis), which looms at 4,413 feet (1,345 m). &#91;11&#93; The region is also peppered with numerous lakes, known as [lochs](/Loch)—a term also applied to the many saltwater inlets that scar the country's deeply indented western coastline. The geography of the islands is varied. Some, like [Mull](/Isle_of_Mull) and [Skye](/Isle_of_Skye), are known for their dramatic, mountainous terrain, while others, such as [Tiree](/Tiree) and [Coll](/Coll), are disconcertingly flat.

### Etymology

*   Main article: [Etymology of Scotland](/Etymology_of_Scotland)

The name *Scotland* is derived from *[Scoti](/Scoti)*, the Latin designation for the [Gaels](/Gaels). &#91;22&#93; One [Philip Freeman](/Philip_Freeman) has speculated, likely on a slow Tuesday, that a band of raiders might have adopted a name from an [Indo-European root](/Indo-European_root), *\*skot*, pointing to a parallel in the Greek *skotos* (σκότος), which means 'darkness, gloom'. &#91;23&#93; An entirely fitting origin story. The [Late Latin](/Late_Latin) term *[Scotia](/Scotia)* ("land of the Gaels") was originally used to describe Ireland, &#91;24&#93; and similarly, in early [Old English](/Old_English_language), *Scotland* referred to Ireland. &#91;25&#93; By the 11th century, at the latest, *Scotia* was being used to denote the Gaelic-speaking part of Scotland north of the [River Forth](/River_Firth), alongside *Albania* or *Albany*, both derived from the Gaelic *[Alba](/Alba)*. &#91;26&#93; The application of the words *Scots* and *Scotland* to encompass the entirety of its modern borders became commonplace during the [Late Middle Ages](/Scotland_in_the_Late_Middle_Ages), as geography finally caught up with nomenclature. &#91;15&#93;

### History

*   Main article: [History of Scotland](/History_of_Scotland)
*   For a chronological guide, see [Timeline of Scottish history](/Timeline_of_Scottish_history).

#### Prehistory

The earliest confirmed sign of human activity in what is now Scotland consists of [Hamburgian culture](/Hamburgian_culture) stone tools. These were crafted by late [Upper Paleolithic](/Upper_Paleolithic) [hunter-gatherers](/Hunter-gatherer) who wandered into the region during the [Bølling–Allerød Interstadial](/B%C3%B8lling%E2%80%93Aller%C3%B8d_Interstadial), a brief warm spell at the end of the [last ice age](/Last_ice_age), around 14,500 to 14,000 years ago. They arrived shortly after the glacial retreat, presumably finding the newly exposed rock and mud appealing. &#91;27&#93; &#91;28&#93;

[Neolithic farmers](/Early_European_Farmers) arrived around 6,000 years ago, bringing with them the revolutionary concepts of agriculture and permanent settlement. &#91;29&#93; The remarkably well-preserved village of [Skara Brae](/Skara_Brae) on the mainland of [Orkney](/Orkney) dates from this era. Neolithic habitation, burial, and ritual sites are particularly abundant and well-preserved in the [Northern Isles](/Northern_Isles) and [Western Isles](/Western_Isles), where a distinct lack of trees forced the inhabitants to build everything from local stone, a testament to stubborn ingenuity. &#91;30&#93; Evidence of sophisticated pre-Christian belief systems is starkly demonstrated by sites like the [Callanish Stones](/Callanish_Stones) on [Lewis](/Isle_of_Lewis) and the tomb of [Maes Howe](/Maes_Howe) on [Orkney](/Orkney), both constructed in the third millennium BC, proving that humanity has been arranging rocks in impressively enigmatic patterns for a very long time. &#91;31&#93; <sup>:38</sup>

#### Early history

*   Main articles: [Scotland during the Roman Empire](/Scotland_during_the_Roman_Empire), [Roman Britain](/Roman_Britain), and [Pictland](/Pictland)

![Skara Brae](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Skara_Brae_-_Tombes_n%C3%A9olithiques.jpg/220px-Skara_Brae_-_Tombes_n%C3%A9olithiques.jpg)
[Skara Brae](/Skara_Brae), Europe's most complete [Neolithic](/Neolithic) village, occupied from roughly 3180 BC – 2500 BC.

The first written mention of Scotland appeared in 320 BC from the Greek sailor [Pytheas](/Pytheas), who called the northern tip of Britain "Orcas," which became the source for the name of the Orkney islands. He was just passing through. &#91;32&#93; <sup>:10</sup>

Most of what we now call Scotland was never formally [incorporated](/Roman_conquest_of_Britain) into the [Roman Empire](/Roman_Empire), and Roman control over the parts they did reach was fleeting and fluctuated wildly. The first Roman incursion occurred in 79 AD, when [Agricola](/Gnaeus_Julius_Agricola) invaded. He managed to defeat a Caledonian army at the [Battle of Mons Graupius](/Battle_of_Mons_Graupius) in 83 AD. &#91;32&#93; <sup>:12</sup> Following this victory, Roman forts were briefly established along the [Gask Ridge](/Gask_Ridge) near the [Highland line](/Highland_Boundary_Fault), but within three years, the Roman armies had retreated to the [Southern Uplands](/Southern_Uplands), presumably tired of the weather and the locals. &#91;33&#93; The remains of Roman forts from the 1st century have been discovered as far north as the [Moray Firth](/Moray_Firth), marking the high tide of their ambition. &#91;34&#93; By the reign of [Emperor](/Roman_emperor) [Trajan](/Trajan) (r. 98–117), Roman control had receded to Britain south of a line between the [River Tyne](/River_Tyne) and the [Solway Firth](/Solway_Firth). &#91;35&#93; Along this line, Trajan's successor [Hadrian](/Hadrian) (r. 117–138) constructed [Hadrian's Wall](/Hadrian%27s_Wall) in northern England, &#91;32&#93; <sup>:12</sup> and the *[Limes Britannicus](/Limes_Britannicus)* became the northern frontier of their empire, a very large "do not cross" sign. &#91;36&#93; &#91;37&#93; Roman influence in the southern part of the country was nonetheless considerable, and they are credited with introducing [Christianity](/Christianity) to the region, an import that would have lasting consequences. &#91;32&#93; <sup>:13–14</sup> &#91;31&#93; <sup>:38</sup>

The [Antonine Wall](/Antonine_Wall) was constructed from 142 AD on the orders of Hadrian's successor, [Antoninus Pius](/Antoninus_Pius) (r. 138–161), in an attempt to defend the Roman-held part of Scotland from the unadministered territories north of a line between the [Firth of Clyde](/Firth_of_Clyde) and the [Firth of Forth](/Firth_of_Forth). &#91;38&#93; This wall, too, was eventually abandoned. The [Roman invasion of Caledonia from 208–210](/Roman_invasion_of_Caledonia_208%E2%80%93210) was launched by emperors of the [Severan dynasty](/Severan_dynasty) after the Caledonians broke a treaty in 197. &#91;34&#93; However, a permanent conquest of the whole island was thwarted as Roman forces became mired in punishing [guerrilla warfare](/Guerrilla_warfare). The death of the senior emperor [Septimius Severus](/Septimius_Severus) (r. 193–211) at [Eboracum](/Eboracum) ([York](/York)) after falling ill on campaign put a definitive end to the endeavor. Although the [Roman army](/Roman_army) established forts near those built by Agricola, clustered at the mouths of the Highland [glens](/Glens), the Caledonians were in revolt again in 210–211 and these were swiftly overrun. &#91;34&#93;

![Callanish Stones](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e5/Callanish_Stones%2C_Isle_of_Lewis%2C_Scotland_-_Diliff.jpg/220px-Callanish_Stones%2C_Isle_of_Lewis%2C_Scotland_-_Diliff.jpg)
[Callanish Stones](/Callanish_Stones), erected in the late [Neolithic](/Neolithic) era, a long-term public art project.

To Roman historians like [Tacitus](/Tacitus) and [Cassius Dio](/Cassius_Dio), the [Scottish Highlands](/Scottish_Highlands) and the area north of the [River Forth](/River_Forth) was known as [Caledonia](/Caledonia). &#91;34&#93; Cassius Dio reported that the inhabitants of Caledonia were the [Caledonians](/Caledonians) and the [Maeatae](/Maeatae). &#91;34&#93; Other ancient writers used the adjective "Caledonian" to refer to anywhere in northern or inland Britain, often mentioning the region's people, animals, cold climate, pearls, and a notable area of wooded hills ([Latin](/Latin_language): *saltus*) which the 2nd-century philosopher [Ptolemy](/Ptolemy), in his *Geography*, placed south-west of the [Beauly Firth](/Beauly_Firth). &#91;34&#93; The name Caledonia echoes in modern place names like [Dunkeld](/Dunkeld), [Rohallion](/Rohallion), and [Schiehallion](/Schiehallion). &#91;34&#93;

The [Great Conspiracy](/Great_Conspiracy) of the later 4th century was a seemingly coordinated invasion against Roman rule in Britain, involving the Gaelic [Scoti](/Scoti) and the Caledonians, who by then were known to the Romans as [Picts](/Picts). This was put down by the *comes* Theodosius, but Roman military government was withdrawn from the island entirely by the early 5th century. This power vacuum resulted in the [Anglo-Saxon settlement of Britain](/Anglo-Saxon_settlement_of_Britain) and the immigration of the [Saxons](/Saxons) to southeastern Scotland and the rest of eastern Great Britain. &#91;35&#93;

#### Kingdom of Scotland

*   Main articles: [Kingdom of Scotland](/Kingdom_of_Scotland), [Scotland in the Early Middle Ages](/Scotland_in_the_Early_Middle_Ages), [Scotland in the High Middle Ages](/Scotland_in_the_High_Middle_Ages), and [Scotland in the Late Middle Ages](/Scotland_in_the_Late_Middle_Ages)

![Political divisions in early medieval Scotland](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Scotland_600_AD.svg/220px-Scotland_600_AD.svg.png)
Political divisions in early medieval Scotland. A complicated map for a complicated time.

![Norse kingdoms at the end of the eleventh century](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Norse_Scotland_11thC.PNG/220px-Norse_Scotland_11thC.PNG)
Norse kingdoms at the end of the eleventh century.

Beginning in the sixth century, the area now known as Scotland was a fractured landscape of competing powers: [Pictland](/Pictland), a mosaic of petty lordships in central Scotland; &#91;32&#93; <sup>:25–26</sup> the [Anglo-Saxon](/Anglo-Saxon) [Kingdom of Northumbria](/Kingdom_of_Northumbria), which had conquered southeastern Scotland; &#91;32&#93; <sup>:18–20</sup> a Northern Brittonic territory likely centered on [Alt Clut](/Alt_Clut) (Dumbarton Rock) and the Clyde valley; &#91;39&#93; and [Dál Riata](/D%C3%A1l_Riata), which spanned western Scotland and northern Ireland, effectively exporting Gaelic language and culture into Scotland. &#91;40&#93; These societies were structured around the family unit and featured stark divisions of wealth, though the vast majority were poor, engaged in full-time [subsistence agriculture](/Subsistence_agriculture). The Picts, it should be noted, kept slaves (mostly captured in war) through the ninth century. &#91;32&#93; <sup>:26–27</sup>

Gaelic influence over Pictland and Northumbria was advanced by a significant number of [Gaelic-speaking clerics](/Celtic_Church) working as missionaries. &#91;32&#93; <sup>:23–24</sup> Operating from the island of [Iona](/Iona) in the sixth century, [Saint Columba](/Saint_Columba) was one of the earliest and most renowned of these figures. &#91;31&#93; <sup>:39</sup> The [Vikings](/Vikings) began raiding Scotland in the eighth century. While they sought slaves and luxury goods, their primary motivation was land acquisition. The oldest [Norse](/Norse_Scotland) settlements were in northwest Scotland, but they eventually conquered many coastal areas. [Old Norse](/Old_Norse) completely supplanted the [Pictish language](/Pictish_language) in the [Northern Isles](/Northern_Isles). &#91;41&#93;

In the ninth century, the Norse threat created a power vacuum that allowed a Gael named [Kenneth I](/Kenneth_I) (Cináed mac Ailpín) to seize control over Pictland. This established a royal dynasty to which modern monarchs trace their lineage and signaled the beginning of the end for Pictish culture as a distinct entity. &#91;32&#93; <sup>:31–32</sup> &#91;42&#93; The kingdom of Cináed and his descendants, known as Alba, was Gaelic in character but occupied the same territory as Pictland. By the end of the tenth century, the Pictish language had become extinct, its speakers having shifted to Gaelic. &#91;32&#93; <sup>:32–33</sup> From its base in eastern Scotland, north of the [River Forth](/River_Forth) and south of the [River Spey](/River_Spey), the kingdom expanded south into former Northumbrian lands and north into [Moray](/Province_of_Moray). &#91;32&#93; <sup>:34–35</sup> Around the turn of the millennium, agricultural lands became more centralized and the first towns began to emerge. &#91;32&#93; <sup>:36–37</sup>

![James V of Scotland](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/James_V_at_the_Court_of_Session.jpg/220px-James_V_at_the_Court_of_Session.jpg)
[James V of Scotland](/James_V_of_Scotland) at the [Court of Session](/Court_of_Session) in 1532, at [Parliament House, Edinburgh](/Parliament_House,_Edinburgh), the home of the [Parliament of Scotland](/Parliament_of_Scotland) until 1707.

During the twelfth and thirteenth centuries, much of Scotland fell under the control of a single ruler. Initially, Gaelic culture held sway, but a steady stream of immigrants from France, England, and Flanders created a more diverse society. The Gaelic language began to be replaced by Scots, and a modern nation-state started to take shape. At the end of this period, a protracted war with England ignited the growth of a [Scottish national consciousness](/Scottish_national_consciousness). &#91;43&#93; &#91;44&#93; <sup>:ch 1</sup> [David I](/David_I_of_Scotland) (1124–1153) and his successors centralized royal power &#91;43&#93; <sup>:41–42</sup> and unified mainland Scotland, capturing regions like Moray, [Galloway](/Galloway), and [Caithness](/Caithness). He was unable, however, to extend his authority over the [Hebrides](/Hebrides), which had been ruled by various [Scottish clans](/Scottish_clans) following the death of [Somerled](/Somerled) in 1164. &#91;43&#93; <sup>:48–49</sup> In 1266, Scotland fought the brief but significant [Scottish-Norwegian War](/Scottish-Norwegian_War), which resulted in the reclamation of the [Hebrides](/Hebrides) after a decisive defeat of King [Haakon IV](/Haakon_IV) and his forces at the [Battle of Largs](/Battle_of_Largs). &#91;45&#93; Until then, the Hebrides had been under Norwegian Viking control for roughly 400 years, developing a unique [Norse–Gaelic](/Norse%E2%80%93Gaelic) culture that introduced many [Old Norse](/Old_Norse) loanwords into the [Scottish Gaelic](/Scottish_Gaelic) spoken by the islanders. Over successive generations, the Norse became almost entirely assimilated into [Gaelic culture](/Gaelic_culture) and the [Scottish clan](/Scottish_clan) system. After the war, Scotland had to affirm Norwegian sovereignty over the [Northern Isles](/Northern_Isles), but these were later integrated into Scotland in the 15th century. Scandinavian culture, in the form of the [Norn language](/Norn_language), survived much longer there than in the Hebrides and would heavily influence the local [Scots](/Scots_language) dialect on [Shetland](/Shetland) and [Orkney](/Orkney). &#91;46&#93; A system of [feudalism](/Feudalism) was later consolidated, with both Anglo-Norman incomers and native Gaelic chieftains granted land in exchange for service to the king. &#91;43&#93; <sup>:53–54</sup> The relationship with the [Kingdom of England](/Kingdom_of_England) during this period was complex; Scottish kings repeatedly, and sometimes successfully, attempted to exploit English political turmoil. This was followed by the longest period of peace between the two nations in the medieval era, from 1217 to 1296. &#91;43&#93; <sup>:45-46</sup>

#### Wars of Scottish Independence

*   Main articles: [Wars of Scottish Independence](/Wars_of_Scottish_Independence), [First War of Scottish Independence](/First_War_of_Scottish_Independence), and [Second War of Scottish Independence](/Second_War_of_Scottish_Independence)

![The Wallace Monument](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Wallace_Monument_from_Stirling_Castle.jpg/220px-Wallace_Monument_from_Stirling_Castle.jpg)
The [Wallace Monument](/Wallace_Monument) in [Stirling](/Stirling), commemorating Sir [William Wallace](/William_Wallace), a Scottish independence leader who became a national icon. &#91;47&#93;

The death of [Alexander III](/Alexander_III_of_Scotland) in March 1286 shattered the succession line of Scotland's kings. [Edward I of England](/Edward_I_of_England), sensing an opportunity, arbitrated among the various claimants to the Scottish throne. In exchange for surrendering Scotland's nominal independence, [John Balliol](/John_Balliol) was declared king in 1292, a decision that went about as well as you'd expect. &#91;43&#93; <sup>:47</sup> &#91;48&#93; In 1294, Balliol and other Scottish lords refused Edward's demands to serve in his army against the French. In response, Scotland and France sealed a treaty on 23 October 1295, known as the [Auld Alliance](/Auld_Alliance). War inevitably followed, and John was deposed by Edward, who then took personal control of Scotland. [Andrew Moray](/Andrew_Moray) and [William Wallace](/William_Wallace) emerged as the primary leaders of the resistance to English rule in the [Wars of Scottish Independence](/Wars_of_Scottish_Independence), &#91;49&#93; until [Robert the Bruce](/Robert_the_Bruce) was crowned king of Scotland in 1306. &#91;50&#93; A decisive victory at the [Battle of Bannockburn](/Battle_of_Bannockburn) in 1314 proved that the Scots had regained control of their kingdom. In 1320, the world's first documented declaration of independence, the [Declaration of Arbroath](/Declaration_of_Arbroath), secured the support of [Pope John XXII](/Pope_John_XXII), leading to the legal recognition of Scottish sovereignty by the English Crown. &#91;51&#93; <sup>:70, 72</sup>

A civil war between the [Bruce dynasty](/Bruce_dynasty) and their long-standing rivals, the [House of Comyn](/House_of_Comyn) and [House of Balliol](/House_of_Balliol), dragged on until the mid-14th century. Although the Bruce faction ultimately prevailed, [David II](/David_II_of_Scotland)'s lack of an heir allowed his half-nephew [Robert II](/Robert_II_of_Scotland), the [Lord High Steward of Scotland](/Lord_High_Steward_of_Scotland), to ascend to the throne and establish the [House of Stewart](/House_of_Stewart). &#91;51&#93; <sup>:77</sup> The Stewarts would rule Scotland for the remainder of the [Middle Ages](/Middle_Ages). The country they governed experienced a period of greater prosperity from the end of the 14th century, through the Scottish Renaissance, to the [Reformation](/Scottish_Reformation), &#91;52&#93; <sup>:93</sup> despite the devastating effects of the [Black Death](/Black_Death) in 1349 &#91;51&#93; <sup>:76</sup> and an increasing cultural and political division between the [Highlands](/Scottish_Highlands) and the [Lowlands](/Scottish_Lowlands). &#91;51&#93; <sup>:78</sup> Multiple truces managed to reduce the frequency of warfare on the southern border. &#91;51&#93; <sup>:76, 83</sup>

#### Union of the Crowns

*   Main articles: [Scotland in the early modern period](/Scotland_in_the_early_modern_period) and [Union of the Crowns](/Union_of_the_Crowns)

![James VI](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/James_VI_of_Scotland_as_a_boy%2C_1574.jpg/220px-James_VI_of_Scotland_as_a_boy%2C_1574.jpg)
[James VI](/James_VI_and_I), [King of Scotland](/King_of_Scotland), who succeeded to the English and Irish thrones in 1603, looking unimpressed even then.

The [Treaty of Perpetual Peace](/Treaty_of_Perpetual_Peace) was signed in 1502 by [James IV of Scotland](/James_IV_of_Scotland) and [Henry VII of England](/Henry_VII_of_England). As part of the deal, James married Henry's daughter, [Margaret Tudor](/Margaret_Tudor). &#91;53&#93; This "perpetual peace" lasted just over a decade. James later invaded England in support of France under the terms of the [Auld Alliance](/Auld_Alliance) and became the last monarch in [Great Britain](/Great_Britain) to die in battle, at [Flodden](/Battle_of_Flodden) in 1513. &#91;54&#93; The subsequent war with England during the minority years of [Mary, Queen of Scots](/Mary,_Queen_of_Scots), from 1543 to 1551, is known with grim accuracy as the [Rough Wooing](/Rough_Wooing). &#91;55&#93; In 1560, the [Treaty of Edinburgh](/Treaty_of_Edinburgh) concluded the [Siege of Leith](/Siege_of_Leith) and recognized the Protestant [Elizabeth I](/Elizabeth_I) as Queen of England. &#91;52&#93; <sup>:112</sup> The [Parliament of Scotland](/Scottish_Reformation_Parliament) convened and promptly adopted the [Scots Confession](/Scots_Confession), signaling the [Scottish Reformation](/Scottish_Reformation)'s decisive break from papal authority and Roman Catholic doctrine. &#91;31&#93; <sup>:44</sup> The Catholic Mary, Queen of Scots, was forced to [abdicate in 1567](/Act_Anent_the_demission_of_the_Crown_in_favour_of_our_Sovereign_Lord,_and_his_Majesty%27s_Coronation_1567). &#91;56&#93;

In 1603, [James VI, King of Scots](/James_VI_and_I), inherited the thrones of the [Kingdom of England](/Kingdom_of_England) and the [Kingdom of Ireland](/Kingdom_of_Ireland) in the [Union of the Crowns](/Union_of_the_Crowns) and promptly relocated to London. &#91;57&#93; This was a [personal union](/Personal_union); despite sharing a monarch, the kingdoms retained their separate parliaments, laws, and institutions. The first [Union Jack](/Union_Jack) was designed at James's request, to be flown alongside the [St Andrew's Cross](/Flag_of_Scotland) on Scots vessels at sea. James VI and I harbored ambitions of creating a single kingdom of Great Britain but was thwarted by the [Parliament of England](/Parliament_of_England). They supported a wrecking proposal for a full legal union instead, a proposition the Scots Parliament would not accept, forcing the king to abandon the plan. &#91;58&#93;

With the exception of a brief period under [the Protectorate](/The_Protectorate), Scotland remained a separate state in the 17th century. However, there was significant conflict between the crown and the [Covenanters](/Covenanters) over the form of [church government](/Presbyterian_church_governance). &#91;59&#93; <sup>:124</sup> The military was strengthened, enabling the imposition of royal authority on the western Highland clans. The 1609 [Statutes of Iona](/Statutes_of_Iona) compelled the cultural integration of Hebridean clan leaders. &#91;60&#93; <sup>:37–40</sup> In 1641 and again in 1643, the Parliament of Scotland unsuccessfully sought a "federative" rather than "incorporating" union with England, in which Scotland would retain a separate parliament. &#91;61&#93; The issue of union fractured the parliament in 1648. &#91;61&#93;

Following the execution of the Scottish king at [Whitehall](/Whitehall) in 1649, amidst the [Wars of the Three Kingdoms](/Wars_of_the_Three_Kingdoms) and [its events in Scotland](/Scotland_in_the_Wars_of_the_Three_Kingdoms), [Oliver Cromwell](/Oliver_Cromwell), the victorious [Lord Protector](/Lord_Protector), imposed the British Isles' first written constitution—the [Instrument of Government](/Instrument_of_Government)—on Scotland in 1652 as part of the republican [Commonwealth of England, Scotland, and Ireland](/Commonwealth_of_England,_Scotland,_and_Ireland). &#91;61&#93; The Protectorate Parliament was the first Westminster parliament to include representatives nominally from Scotland. The monarchy of the [House of Stuart](/House_of_Stuart) was resumed with the [Restoration in Scotland](/Restoration_in_Scotland) in 1660. The Parliament of Scotland sought a commercial union with England in 1664; the proposal was rejected in 1668. &#91;61&#93; In 1670, the Parliament of England rejected a proposed political union with Scotland. &#91;61&#93; Similar English proposals were abandoned in 1674 and 1685. &#91;61&#93; The Scots Parliament rejected proposals for a political union with England in 1689. &#91;61&#93; [Jacobitism](/Jacobitism), the political support for the exiled Catholic Stuart dynasty, remained a persistent threat to the security of the British state under the Protestant [House of Orange](/House_of_Orange) and the succeeding [House of Hanover](/House_of_Hanover) until the final defeat of the [Jacobite rising of 1745](/Jacobite_rising_of_1745). &#91;61&#93; In 1698, the [Company of Scotland](/Company_of_Scotland) launched an ambitious project to establish a trading colony on the [Isthmus of Panama](/Isthmus_of_Panama). Nearly every Scottish landowner with spare cash is said to have invested in the ill-fated [Darien scheme](/Darien_scheme). &#91;62&#93; &#91;63&#93;

#### Treaty of Union

*   Main article: [Treaty of Union](/Treaty_of_Union)
*   Further information: [Kingdom of Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain)

![Scottish Exemplification of the Treaty of Union of 1707](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Treaty_of_Union_1707.jpg/220px-Treaty_of_Union_1707.jpg)
Scottish Exemplification (official copy) of the Treaty of Union of 1707.

After another proposal from the English House of Lords was rejected in 1695, and a further Lords motion was voted down in the House of Commons in 1700, the Parliament of Scotland once again rejected union in 1702. &#91;61&#93; The catastrophic failure of the Darien Scheme bankrupted the landowners who had invested, though not the burghs. This financial ruin, combined with the threat of an English invasion, played a decisive role in persuading the Scots elite to support a union with England. &#91;62&#93; &#91;63&#93; On 22 July 1706, the [Treaty of Union](/Treaty_of_Union) was agreed upon between representatives of the [Scots Parliament](/Parliament_of_Scotland) and the [Parliament of England](/Parliament_of_England). The following year, twin [Acts of Union](/Acts_of_Union_1707) were passed by both parliaments, creating the united [Kingdom of Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain) effective from 1 May 1707, &#91;64&#93; despite popular opposition and anti-union riots in [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh), [Glasgow](/Glasgow), and elsewhere. &#91;65&#93; &#91;66&#93; The union also created the [Parliament of Great Britain](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain), which superseded both the Parliament of Scotland and the Parliament of England, and which rejected proposals from the [Parliament of Ireland](/Parliament_of_Ireland) that the third kingdom be incorporated into the union. &#91;61&#93;

![James Ogilvy](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/James_Ogilvy%2C_4th_Earl_of_Findlater_and_1st_Earl_of_Seafield_by_Sir_Godfrey_Kneller.jpg/170px-James_Ogilvy%2C_4th_Earl_of_Findlater_and_1st_Earl_of_Seafield_by_Sir_Godfrey_Kneller.jpg)
[James Ogilvy](/James_Ogilvy,_4th_Earl_of_Findlater), former [Lord Chancellor](/Lord_Chancellor_of_Scotland) (1702–1708), initially supported the union but by 1713 was advocating for its reversal. A change of heart.

[Andrew Fletcher](/Andrew_Fletcher_(patriot)), a prominent Scottish patriot, argued that the treaty's ratification would render Scotland "more like a conquered province," a sentiment that proved enduring. &#91;67&#93; By 1713, the former [Lord Chancellor of Scotland](/Lord_Chancellor_of_Scotland), [James Ogilvy, 4th Earl of Findlater](/James_Ogilvy,_4th_Earl_of_Findlater), a key supporter of the treaty, had reversed his position and unsuccessfully advocated for its repeal. &#91;68&#93; The deposed [Jacobite Stuart](/Jacobitism) claimants remained popular in the Highlands and north-east, particularly among non-[Presbyterians](/Presbyterian), including Roman Catholics and [Episcopalian Protestants](/Episcopalian_Protestants). Two major Jacobite risings, launched in [1715](/Jacobite_rising_of_1715) and [1745](/Jacobite_rising_of_1745), failed to dislodge the [House of Hanover](/House_of_Hanover) from the British throne. The threat of the Jacobite movement to the United Kingdom and its monarchs effectively ended at the [Battle of Culloden](/Battle_of_Culloden), Great Britain's last [pitched battle](/Pitched_battle).

The passing of the Treaty of Union did not usher in immediate economic prosperity, as had been widely speculated by the [pamphleteers](/Pamphleteer), largely due to the scant consideration given to the prospects of the Scottish economy. &#91;69&#93; Proponents of the union believed economic advantages would follow, particularly in the wake of the disastrous [Darien scheme](/Darien_scheme) which had left the Kingdom of Scotland bankrupt. &#91;67&#93; Eventually, however, with trade tariffs with England abolished, trade did blossom, especially with [Colonial America](/Colonial_America). The clippers owned by Glasgow's [Tobacco Lords](/Tobacco_Lords) were the fastest ships on the route to [Virginia](/Virginia). Until the [American War of Independence](/American_War_of_Independence) in 1776, Glasgow was the world's premier tobacco port, dominating global trade. &#91;70&#93; The wealth disparity between the merchant classes of the Scottish Lowlands and the ancient clans of the Scottish Highlands grew, amplifying centuries of division.

In the Highlands, clan chiefs gradually began to see themselves more as commercial landlords than as leaders of their people. These social and economic shifts included the first phase of the [Highland Clearances](/Highland_Clearances) and, ultimately, led to the demise of the clan system. &#91;71&#93; <sup>:32–53, passim</sup>

#### Industrial age and the Scottish Enlightenment

*   Main article: [Scotland in the modern era](/Scotland_in_the_modern_era)

![Walter Scott](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/Sir_Walter_Scott%2C_1771_-_1832._Novelist_and_poet_by_Sir_Henry_Raeburn.jpg/220px-Sir_Walter_Scott%2C_1771_-_1832._Novelist_and_poet_by_Sir_Henry_Raeburn.jpg)
[Walter Scott](/Walter_Scott), whose [Waverley Novels](/Waverley_Novels) helped define and, some might say, invent Scottish identity in the 19th century.

The [Scottish Enlightenment](/Scottish_Enlightenment) and the [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution) transformed Scotland into an intellectual, commercial, and industrial powerhouse. &#91;72&#93; So much so that [Voltaire](/Voltaire) remarked, "We look to Scotland for all our ideas of civilisation." &#91;73&#93; With the end of Jacobitism and the advent of the Union, thousands of Scots, mainly Lowlanders, took up powerful positions in politics, the civil service, the army and navy, trade, economics, and colonial enterprises across the burgeoning [British Empire](/British_Empire). Historian Neil Davidson notes, "after 1746 there was an entirely new level of participation by Scots in political life, particularly outside Scotland." Davidson also asserts, "far from being 'peripheral' to the British economy, Scotland – or more precisely, the Lowlands – lay at its core." &#91;74&#93;

The [Scottish Reform Act 1832](/Scottish_Reform_Act_1832) increased the number of Scottish MPs and widened the franchise to include more of the middle classes. &#91;75&#93; From the mid-century onwards, there were growing calls for Home Rule for Scotland, and the post of [Secretary of State for Scotland](/Secretary_of_State_for_Scotland) was revived. &#91;76&#93; Towards the end of the century, prime ministers of Scottish descent included [William Gladstone](/William_Ewart_Gladstone) &#91;77&#93; and [the Earl of Rosebery](/Archibald_Primrose,_5th_Earl_of_Rosebery). &#91;78&#93; In the late 19th century, the rising importance of the working classes was marked by [Keir Hardie](/Keir_Hardie)'s success in the [Mid Lanarkshire by-election of 1888](/Mid_Lanarkshire_by-election,_1888), leading to the founding of the [Scottish Labour Party](/Scottish_Labour_Party_(1888)), which was later absorbed into the [Independent Labour Party](/Independent_Labour_Party) in 1895, with Hardie as its first leader. &#91;79&#93;

Glasgow grew into one of the largest cities in the world, known as "the [Second City of the Empire](/Second_City_of_the_Empire)" after London. &#91;80&#93; After 1860, the Clydeside shipyards specialized in steamships made of iron (and after 1870, steel), which rapidly replaced the wooden sailing vessels of both merchant and battle fleets worldwide. It became the world's pre-eminent shipbuilding center. &#91;81&#93; The industrial developments, while bringing work and wealth, were so rapid that housing, town planning, and public health provisions failed to keep pace. For a time, living conditions in some towns and cities were notoriously grim, with overcrowding, high infant mortality, and rising rates of tuberculosis. &#91;82&#93;

While the Scottish Enlightenment is traditionally considered to have concluded by the end of the 18th century, &#91;83&#93; disproportionately large Scottish contributions to British science and letters continued for another 50 years or more. This was thanks to figures such as physicists [James Clerk Maxwell](/James_Clerk_Maxwell) and [Lord Kelvin](/William_Thomson,_1st_Baron_Kelvin), and engineers and inventors [James Watt](/James_Watt) and [William Murdoch](/William_Murdoch), whose work was critical to the technological advancements of the Industrial Revolution throughout Britain. &#91;84&#93; In literature, the most successful figure of the mid-19th century was [Walter Scott](/Walter_Scott). His first prose work, [*Waverley*](/Waverley_(novel)) in 1814, is often called the first historical novel. &#91;85&#93; It launched a highly successful career that arguably did more than any other to define and popularize Scottish cultural identity. &#91;86&#93; In the late 19th century, a number of Scottish-born authors achieved international reputations, including [Robert Louis Stevenson](/Robert_Louis_Stevenson), [Arthur Conan Doyle](/Arthur_Conan_Doyle), [J. M. Barrie](/J._M._Barrie), and [George MacDonald](/George_MacDonald). &#91;87&#93; Scotland also played a major role in the development of art and architecture. The [Glasgow School](/Glasgow_School), which developed in the late 19th century and flourished in the early 20th, produced a distinctive blend of influences including the [Celtic Revival](/Celtic_Revival), the [Arts and Crafts movement](/Arts_and_Crafts_movement), and [Japonism](/Japonism). This style found favor throughout the [modern art](/Modern_art) world of continental Europe and helped define the [Art Nouveau](/Art_Nouveau) style. Its proponents included the architect and artist [Charles Rennie Mackintosh](/Charles_Rennie_Mackintosh). &#91;88&#93;

#### World wars and Scotland Act 1998

![A piper of the Seaforth Highlanders](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Battle_of_Bazentin_Ridge._A_piper_of_the_7th_Seaforth_Highlanders.jpg/220px-Battle_of_Bazentin_Ridge._A_piper_of_the_7th_Seaforth_Highlanders.jpg)
A piper of the [Seaforth Highlanders](/Seaforth_Highlanders) leads the [26th Brigade](/26th_Infantry_Brigade_(United_Kingdom)) back from the trenches during the [Battle of Bazentin Ridge](/Battle_of_Bazentin_Ridge), July 1916.

Scotland played a significant role in the [British effort](/History_of_the_United_Kingdom_during_the_First_World_War) during the [First World War](/First_World_War), primarily providing manpower, ships, machinery, fish, and money. &#91;89&#93; With a population of 4.8 million in 1911, Scotland sent over half a million men to the war; over a quarter of them died in combat or from disease, and 150,000 were seriously wounded. &#91;90&#93; [Field Marshal](/Field_Marshal_(United_Kingdom)) [Sir Douglas Haig](/Douglas_Haig) was Britain's commander on the Western Front. The war also saw the emergence of a radical movement known as "[Red Clydeside](/Red_Clydeside)," led by militant trade unionists. Formerly a [Liberal](/Liberal_Party_(UK)) stronghold, the industrial districts shifted to [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) by 1922, with a base among the [Irish Catholic](/Irish_Catholic) working-class districts. Women were particularly active in building neighborhood solidarity on housing issues. The "Reds" operated within the Labour Party but had little influence in Parliament, and the mood shifted to one of passive despair by the late 1920s. &#91;91&#93;

During the Second World War, Scotland was targeted by [Nazi Germany](/Nazi_Germany), largely due to its factories, shipyards, and coal mines. &#91;92&#93; Cities like [Glasgow](/Glasgow) and [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh) were targeted by German bombers, as were smaller towns, mostly located in the central belt of the country. &#91;92&#93; Perhaps the most significant air raid in Scotland was the [Clydebank Blitz](/Clydebank_Blitz) of March 1941, which aimed to destroy naval shipbuilding in the area. &#91;93&#93; The raid killed 528 people and destroyed 4,000 homes. &#91;93&#93; In what is arguably Scotland's most bizarre wartime episode, [Rudolf Hess](/Rudolf_Hess) flew to Renfrewshire in 1941, possibly intending to broker a peace deal through the [Duke of Hamilton](/Douglas_Douglas-Hamilton,_14th_Duke_of_Hamilton). &#91;94&#93; Before his departure, Hess had given his adjutant, [Karlheinz Pintsch](/Karlheinz_Pintsch), a letter for [Adolf Hitler](/Adolf_Hitler) detailing his intentions. Pintsch delivered the letter to Hitler at the Berghof around noon on 11 May. &#91;95&#93; [Albert Speer](/Albert_Speer) later recalled Hitler describing Hess's departure as one of the worst personal blows of his life, viewing it as a personal betrayal. &#91;96&#93; Hitler worried that his allies, Italy and Japan, would perceive Hess's act as a secret attempt by him to open peace negotiations with the British.

![Reconvening of the Scottish Parliament](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Donald_Dewar%2C_Queen_Elizabeth_II_and_David_Steel_at_the_opening_of_the_Scottish_Parliament_-_1st_July_1999.jpg/220px-Donald_Dewar%2C_Queen_Elizabeth_II_and_David_Steel_at_the_opening_of_the_Scottish_Parliament_-_1st_July_1999.jpg)
Reconvening of the [Scottish Parliament](/Scottish_Parliament) in July 1999 with [Donald Dewar](/Donald_Dewar), [first minister](/First_minister_of_Scotland) (left) and [Queen Elizabeth II](/Queen_Elizabeth_II) (centre).

After 1945, Scotland's economic situation deteriorated due to overseas competition, inefficient industry, and industrial disputes. &#91;97&#93; Only in recent decades has the country experienced something of a cultural and economic renaissance. Economic factors contributing to this recovery included a resurgent financial services industry, [electronics manufacturing](/Electronics_manufacturing) (see [Silicon Glen](/Silicon_Glen)), &#91;98&#93; and the [North Sea oil](/North_Sea_oil) and gas industry. &#91;99&#93; The introduction of the [Community Charge](/Poll_tax_(Great_Britain)) (widely known as the Poll Tax) by Margaret Thatcher's government in 1989, a year before the rest of Great Britain, &#91;100&#93; contributed to a growing movement for Scottish control over its domestic affairs. &#91;101&#93; On 21 December 1988, [Pan Am Flight 103](/Pan_Am_Flight_103) exploded mid-air over the town of [Lockerbie](/Lockerbie), killing everyone on board and eleven residents on the ground. It remains the deadliest [terrorist attack in the United Kingdom](/Terrorism_in_the_United_Kingdom). &#91;102&#93;

Following a [referendum on devolution proposals in 1997](/Scottish_devolution_referendum,_1997), the [Scotland Act 1998](/Scotland_Act_1998) &#91;103&#93; was passed by the British Parliament, establishing a devolved [Scottish Parliament](/Scottish_Parliament) and [Scottish Government](/Scottish_Government) with responsibility for most laws specific to Scotland. &#91;104&#93; The Scottish Parliament was reconvened in [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh) on 4 July 1999. &#91;105&#93; The first person to hold the office of [first minister of Scotland](/First_minister_of_Scotland) was [Donald Dewar](/Donald_Dewar), who served until his sudden death in 2000. &#91;106&#93;

#### 21st century

![Signing of the Edinburgh Agreement](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Signing_of_Edinburgh_Agreement.jpg/220px-Signing_of_Edinburgh_Agreement.jpg)
The signing of the [Edinburgh Agreement](/Edinburgh_Agreement_(2012)) permitted a [referendum on independence](/2014_Scottish_independence_referendum) to be held in 2014. A moment of profound optimism for some, profound dread for others.

The [Scottish Parliament Building](/Scottish_Parliament_Building) at Holyrood opened in October 2004 after lengthy construction delays and significant budget overruns, a fitting start. &#91;107&#93; The Scottish Parliament's form of [proportional representation](/Proportional_representation) (the [additional member system](/Additional_member_system)) ensured that no single party held an overall majority for the first three parliamentary elections.

The pro-[independence](/Scottish_independence) [Scottish National Party](/Scottish_National_Party), led by [Alex Salmond](/Alex_Salmond), defied this trend and achieved an overall majority in the [2011 election](/Scottish_Parliament_election), winning 69 of the 129 available seats. &#91;108&#93; The SNP's success in securing a majority paved the way for the [September 2014 referendum on Scottish independence](/Scottish_independence_referendum,_2014). A majority voted against the proposition, with 55% voting no to independence, settling the question for what turned out to be a very short time. &#91;109&#93; More powers, particularly concerning taxation, were devolved to the Scottish Parliament following the referendum, after cross-party talks in the [Smith Commission](/Smith_Commission).

Since the 2014 referendum, events such as the UK leaving the European Union—despite a majority of voters in Scotland opting to remain—have led to renewed calls for a [second independence referendum](/Proposed_second_Scottish_independence_referendum). In 2022, the [Lord Advocate](/Lord_Advocate), [Dorothy Bain](/Dorothy_Bain), argued the case for the Scottish Government to hold another referendum. The [Supreme Court](/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_Kingdom) subsequently ruled against this argument. &#91;110&#93; Following the Supreme Court's decision, the Scottish Government stated its wish to amend the [Scotland Act 1998](/Scotland_Act_1998) to allow a referendum to be held, a constitutional conversation that continues. &#91;111&#93; &#91;112&#93;

### Geography and natural history

*   Main article: [Geography of Scotland](/Geography_of_Scotland)

![Ben Nevis](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/BenNevis2005.jpg/220px-BenNevis2005.jpg)
At 4,413 feet (1,345 m), [Ben Nevis](/Ben_Nevis) is the highest peak in Scotland and the [British Isles](/British_Isles). A fine place to be cold and windswept.

The mainland of Scotland makes up the northern third of the land mass of the island of Great Britain, which lies off the northwest coast of [Continental Europe](/Continental_Europe). Its total area is 30,977 square miles (80,231 km<sup>2</sup>), with a land area of 30,078 square miles (77,901 km<sup>2</sup>), &#91;4&#93; making it comparable in size to the [Czech Republic](/Czech_Republic). Scotland's only land border is with England, running for 96 miles (154 km) between the basin of the [River Tweed](/River_Tweed) on the east coast and the [Solway Firth](/Solway_Firth) in the west. The Atlantic Ocean borders the west coast, and the [North Sea](/North_Sea) is to the east. The island of Ireland is a mere 13 miles (21 km) from the south-western peninsula of [Kintyre](/Kintyre); &#91;113&#93; Norway is 190 miles (305 km) to the northeast, and the [Faroe Islands](/Faroe_Islands) are 168 miles (270 km) to the north.

The territorial extent of Scotland is generally that which was established by the 1237 [Treaty of York](/Treaty_of_York) between Scotland and the Kingdom of England &#91;48&#93; and the 1266 [Treaty of Perth](/Treaty_of_Perth) between Scotland and Norway. &#91;16&#93; Notable exceptions include the [Isle of Man](/Isle_of_Man), which, having been lost to England in the 14th century, is now a [crown dependency](/Crown_dependency) outside the United Kingdom; the island groups of [Orkney](/Orkney) and [Shetland](/Shetland), acquired from Norway in 1472; &#91;114&#93; and [Berwick-upon-Tweed](/Berwick-upon-Tweed), which, after changing hands several times, was ceded to England in 1482. &#91;115&#93;

The geographical [centre of Scotland](/Centre_of_Scotland) lies a few miles from the village of [Newtonmore](/Newtonmore) in [Badenoch](/Badenoch). &#91;116&#93; Rising to 4,413 feet (1,345 m) above sea level, Scotland's highest point is the summit of [Ben Nevis](/Ben_Nevis), in [Lochaber](/Lochaber). The country's longest river, the [River Tay](/River_Tay), flows for a distance of 117 miles (188 km). &#91;11&#93;

#### Geology and geomorphology

*   Main article: [Geology of Scotland](/Geology_of_Scotland)

![Arthur's Seat, Edinburgh](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Arthur%27s_Seat_and_Salisbury_Crags_from_Calton_Hill.jpg/220px-Arthur%27s_Seat_and_Salisbury_Crags_from_Calton_Hill.jpg)
[Arthur's Seat](/Arthur%27s_Seat), Edinburgh.

![Loch Lomond](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/95/Loch_Lomond%2C_Scotland_-_Sept_2006.jpg/220px-Loch_Lomond%2C_Scotland_-_Sept_2006.jpg)
[Loch Lomond](/Loch_Lomond), a freshwater [loch](/Loch), often considered the boundary between the Lowlands and Highlands. &#91;117&#93;

The entirety of Scotland was covered by ice sheets during the [Pleistocene](/Pleistocene) [ice ages](/Ice_ages), and its landscape is profoundly shaped by glaciation. Geologically, the country is divided into three main sub-divisions: the Highlands and Islands, the Central Lowlands, and the Southern Uplands.

The [Highlands and Islands](/Highlands_and_Islands) lie to the north and west of the [Highland Boundary Fault](/Highland_Boundary_Fault), which runs from [Arran](/Isle_of_Arran) to [Stonehaven](/Stonehaven). This part of Scotland is largely composed of ancient rocks from the [Cambrian](/Cambrian) and [Precambrian](/Precambrian) periods, which were uplifted during the later [C Caledonian orogeny](/Caledonian_orogeny). It is interspersed with [igneous](/Igneous) intrusions of a more recent age, the remnants of which formed mountain massifs such as the [Cairngorms](/Cairngorms) and the [Cuillin](/Cuillin) of Skye. &#91;118&#93; In north-eastern mainland Scotland, the [weathering](/Weathering) of rock that occurred before the [Last Ice Age](/Last_Glacial_Period) has shaped much of the landscape. &#91;119&#93;

A significant exception to the ancient rock formations are the fossil-bearing beds of [Old Red Sandstone](/Old_Red_Sandstone), found principally along the [Moray Firth](/Moray_Firth) coast. The [Highlands](/Scottish_Highlands) are generally mountainous, and the highest elevations in the British Isles are found here. Scotland has over 790 islands, divided into four main groups: [Shetland](/Shetland), [Orkney](/Orkney), the [Inner Hebrides](/Inner_Hebrides), and the [Outer Hebrides](/Outer_Hebrides). There are numerous bodies of freshwater, including [Loch Lomond](/Loch_Lomond) and [Loch Ness](/Loch_Ness). Some parts of the coastline consist of [machair](/Machair_(geography)), a low-lying dune pasture land.

The [Central Lowlands](/Central_Lowlands) is a [rift valley](/Rift_valley) primarily composed of [Paleozoic](/Paleozoic) formations. Many of these sediments have economic significance, as this is where the coal and iron-bearing rocks that fueled Scotland's [industrial revolution](/Industrial_revolution) are located. This area has also experienced intense volcanism; [Arthur's Seat](/Arthur%27s_Seat) in Edinburgh is the remnant of a once much larger volcano. This area is relatively low-lying, although even here, hills such as the [Ochils](/Ochil_Hills) and [Campsie Fells](/Campsie_Fells) are rarely far from view.

The [Southern Uplands](/Southern_Uplands) is a range of hills almost 125 miles (200 km) long, interspersed with broad valleys. They lie south of a second [fault line](/Fault_(geology)) (the Southern Uplands fault) that runs from [Girvan](/Girvan) to [Dunbar](/Dunbar). &#91;120&#93; &#91;121&#93; &#91;122&#93; The geological foundations are largely composed of [Silurian](/Silurian) deposits laid down some 400 to 500 million years ago. The highest point of the Southern Uplands is [Merrick](/Merrick,_Galloway), with an elevation of 843 m (2,766 ft). &#91;15&#93; &#91;123&#93; &#91;124&#93; &#91;125&#93; The Southern Uplands is also home to Scotland's highest village, [Wanlockhead](/Wanlockhead) (430 m or 1,411 ft above sea level). &#91;122&#93;

#### Climate

*   Main article: [Climate of Scotland](/Climate_of_Scotland)

![Tiree](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/Tiree_beach.jpg/220px-Tiree_beach.jpg)
[Tiree](/Tiree) in the [Inner Hebrides](/Inner_Hebrides) is one of the sunniest locations in Scotland. A relative distinction.

The climate of most of Scotland is classified as [temperate](/Temperate) and [oceanic](/Oceanic_climate), and tends to be profoundly changeable. Warmed by the [Gulf Stream](/Gulf_Stream) from the Atlantic, it has much milder winters (but cooler, wetter summers) than areas on similar latitudes, such as [Labrador](/Labrador), southern [Scandinavia](/Scandinavia), the [Moscow region](/Moscow_region) in [Russia](/Russia), and the [Kamchatka Peninsula](/Kamchatka_Peninsula) on the opposite side of [Eurasia](/Eurasia). Temperatures are generally lower than in the rest of the UK. The temperature of −27.2 °C (−17.0 °F) recorded at [Braemar](/Braemar) in the [Grampian Mountains](/Grampian_Mountains) on 11 February 1895 is the coldest ever recorded anywhere in the UK, a record they seem perversely proud of. &#91;126&#93; Winter maxima average 6 °C (43 °F) in the Lowlands, with summer maxima averaging 18 °C (64 °F). The highest temperature recorded was 34.8 °C (94.6 °F) at [Charterhall](/RAF_Charterhall), [Scottish Borders](/Scottish_Borders) on 19 July 2022. &#91;127&#93;

The west of Scotland is typically warmer than the east, owing to the influence of Atlantic [ocean currents](/Ocean_currents) and the colder surface temperatures of the [North Sea](/North_Sea). [Tiree](/Tiree), in the Inner Hebrides, is one of the sunniest places in the country: it recorded more than 300 hours of sunshine in May 1975, an anomaly still spoken of in hushed tones. &#91;128&#93; Rainfall varies widely across Scotland. The western highlands are the wettest, with annual rainfall in a few places exceeding 3,000 mm (120 in). &#91;129&#93; In contrast, much of lowland Scotland receives less than 800 mm (31 in) annually. &#91;130&#93; Heavy snowfall is uncommon in the lowlands but becomes more frequent with altitude. Braemar has an average of 59 snow days per year, &#91;131&#93; while many coastal areas average fewer than 10 days of lying snow per year. &#91;130&#93;

#### Flora and fauna

*   Main articles: [Fauna of Scotland](/Fauna_of_Scotland) and [Flora of Scotland](/Flora_of_Scotland)

![White-tailed sea eagle](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b3/Haliaeetus_albicilla_-_01.jpg/220px-Haliaeetus_albicilla_-_01.jpg)
[White-tailed sea eagle](/White-tailed_sea_eagle).

Scotland's wildlife is typical of the north-west of Europe, though several of the larger mammals, such as the lynx, brown bear, wolf, elk, and walrus, were hunted to extinction in historic times. There are important populations of seals and internationally significant nesting grounds for a variety of seabirds, such as [gannets](/Northern_gannet). &#91;132&#93; The [golden eagle](/Golden_eagle) is something of a national icon, majestic and perpetually aloof. &#91;133&#93;

On the high mountain tops, species including the [ptarmigan](/Rock_ptarmigan), [mountain hare](/Mountain_hare), and [stoat](/Stoat) can be seen in their white winter camouflage. &#91;134&#93; Remnants of the native [Scots pine](/Scots_pine) forest still exist, &#91;135&#93; and within these areas, the [Scottish crossbill](/Scottish_crossbill)—the UK's only [endemic](/Endemism) bird species and [vertebrate](/Vertebrate)—can be found, alongside the [capercaillie](/Western_capercaillie), [Scottish wildcat](/Scottish_wildcat), [red squirrel](/Red_squirrel), and [pine marten](/Pine_marten). &#91;136&#93; &#91;137&#93; &#91;138&#93; Various animals have been re-introduced, including the [white-tailed eagle](/White-tailed_eagle) in 1975 and the [red kite](/Red_kite) in the 1980s. &#91;139&#93; &#91;140&#93; There have also been experimental projects involving the [beaver](/European_beaver) and [wild boar](/Wild_boar), both of which are now relatively widespread. Today, much of the remaining native [Caledonian Forest](/Caledonian_Forest) lies within the [Cairngorms National Park](/Cairngorms_National_Park), with remnants of the forest surviving at 84 locations across Scotland. On the west coast, remnants of ancient Celtic Rainforest persist, particularly on the Taynish peninsula in [Argyll](/Argyll); these forests are exceptionally rare due to high rates of deforestation throughout Scottish history. &#91;141&#93; &#91;142&#93; Scotland now ranks in the lowest 15% of countries in the Biodiversity Intactness Index, a rather bleak achievement. &#91;143&#93; &#91;144&#93;

The flora of the country is varied, incorporating both [deciduous](/Deciduous) and [coniferous](/Coniferous) woodland, as well as [moorland](/Moorland) and [tundra](/Tundra) species. Large-scale commercial tree planting and the management of upland moorland habitat for sheep grazing and [field sport](/Field_sports) activities like [deer stalking](/Deer_stalking) and [driven grouse shooting](/Driven_grouse_shooting) have a significant impact on the distribution of [indigenous](/Indigenous_(ecology)) plants and animals. &#91;145&#93; The UK's tallest tree is a [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) planted beside [Loch Fyne](/Loch_Fyne), Argyll, in the 1870s. The [Fortingall Yew](/Fortingall_Yew) may be 5,000 years old and is likely the oldest living thing in Europe. &#91;146&#93; &#91;147&#93; &#91;148&#93; Although the number of native [vascular plants](/Vascular_plant) is low by world standards, Scotland's substantial [bryophyte](/Bryophyte) flora is of global importance. &#91;149&#93; &#91;150&#93;

### Demographics

*   Main article: [Demographics of Scotland](/Demographics_of_Scotland)
*   See also: [Languages of Scotland](/Languages_of_Scotland), [Religion in Scotland](/Religion_in_Scotland), and [Scottish people](/Scottish_people)

#### Population

![Scotland population cartogram](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Scottish_Council_Areas_by_Population.svg/220px-Scottish_Council_Areas_by_Population.svg.png)
Scotland population [cartogram](/Cartogram). The size of councils is proportional to their population.

During the 1820s, many Scots migrated from Scotland to countries such as [Australia](/Australia), the [United States](/United_States), and [Canada](/Canada), particularly from the Highlands, which remained stubbornly poor compared to the rest of Scotland. &#91;151&#93; The Highlands was the only part of mainland Britain to experience recurrent famine. &#91;152&#93; The region exported a limited range of products, had negligible industrial production, and a growing population that strained its subsistence agriculture. These problems, combined with a desire to "improve" agriculture and profits, were the driving forces behind the ongoing [Highland Clearances](/Highland_Clearances). During this period, much of the Highland population suffered eviction as lands were enclosed, primarily for sheep farming. The first phase of the clearances followed patterns of agricultural change seen throughout Britain. The second phase was driven by overpopulation, the [Highland Potato Famine](/Highland_Potato_Famine), and the collapse of industries that had depended on the wartime economy of the Napoleonic Wars. &#91;153&#93;

The population of Scotland grew steadily in the 19th century, from 1,608,000 in the 1801 census to 2,889,000 in 1851 and 4,472,000 in 1901. &#91;154&#93; Even with industrial development, there were not enough good jobs to go around. As a result, between 1841 and 1931, about 2 million Scots migrated to North America and Australia, while another 750,000 relocated to England. &#91;155&#93; The advent of [refrigeration](/Refrigeration) and imports of lamb, mutton, and wool from overseas caused a collapse in sheep prices in the 1870s, bringing an abrupt halt to the previous sheep farming boom. &#91;156&#93;

Scotland is the most [sparsely populated](/Population_density) [country](/Countries_of_the_United_Kingdom) of the United Kingdom. &#91;157&#93; &#91;158&#93; In August 2012, the Scottish population reached an all-time high of 5.25 million people. &#91;159&#93; The reasons cited were that births were outnumbering deaths, and immigrants were moving to Scotland from overseas. In 2011, 43,700 people moved from Wales, Northern Ireland, or England to live in Scotland. &#91;159&#93; The [most recent census in Scotland](/2021_United_Kingdom_census) was conducted by the Scottish Government and the [National Records of Scotland](/National_Records_of_Scotland) in March 2022. &#91;160&#93; The population of Scotland at the 2022 Census was 5,436,600, the highest ever recorded, &#91;160&#93; surpassing the previous record of 5,295,400 at the 2011 Census. It was 5,062,011 at the 2001 Census. &#91;161&#93; An ONS estimate for 2024 was 5,546,900. &#91;5&#93; In the 2011 Census, 62% of Scotland's population stated their [national identity](/National_identity) as '[Scottish](/Scottish_people) only', 18% as 'Scottish and British', 8% as 'British only', and 4% chose 'other identity only'. &#91;162&#93; In 2011, 4.2% of Scotland's population identified as [White Polish](/White_Polish), [White Irish](/White_Irish), [White: Gypsy or Irish Traveller](/White:_Gypsy_or_Irish_Traveller), or [White Other](/White_Other). Additionally, the number of people belonging to Asian, African, Caribbean or Black, Mixed, or Other ethnic groups doubled, reaching 4%. &#91;163&#93;

Throughout its history, Scotland has had a long tradition of both emigration and immigration. In 2021, the Scottish Government released figures showing that an estimated 41,000 people had immigrated from other countries into Scotland, while an average of 22,100 people had migrated from Scotland. Scottish Government data from 2002 shows a sharp increase in immigration to Scotland by 2021, with 2002 estimates standing at 27,800 immigrants. While immigration increased, emigration from Scotland dropped, with 2002 estimates standing at 26,200 people leaving. &#91;164&#93;

#### Urbanisation

*   See also: [Cities of Scotland](/Cities_of_Scotland) and [List of towns and cities in Scotland by population](/List_of_towns_and_cities_in_Scotland_by_population)

Although [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh) is the capital, the largest city is Glasgow, with just over 584,000 inhabitants. The [Greater Glasgow](/Greater_Glasgow) conurbation, with a population of almost 1.2 million, is home to nearly a quarter of Scotland's population. &#91;165&#93; The [Central Belt](/Central_Belt) is where most of the main towns and cities are located, including Glasgow, Edinburgh, Dundee, and Perth. Scotland's only major city outside the Central Belt is Aberdeen. The [Scottish Lowlands](/Scottish_Lowlands) host 80% of the total population, with the [Central Belt](/Central_Belt) accounting for 3.5 million people.

Generally, only the more accessible and larger islands remain inhabited; currently, fewer than 90 are. The Southern Uplands is essentially rural, dominated by agriculture and forestry. &#91;166&#93; &#91;167&#93; Due to housing problems in Glasgow and Edinburgh, [five new towns](/New_towns_in_the_United_Kingdom) were designated between 1947 and 1966: [East Kilbride](/East_Kilbride), [Glenrothes](/Glenrothes), [Cumbernauld](/Cumbernauld), [Livingston](/Livingston,_West_Lothian), and [Irvine](/Irvine,_North_Ayrshire). &#91;168&#93;

The largest council area by population is [Glasgow City](/Glasgow_City_Council), while [Highland](/Highland_(council_area)) is the largest in terms of geographical area.

