#### Languages

*   Main article: [Languages of Scotland](/Languages_of_Scotland)

![Anglo-Scottish border sign](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/A1_Scotland_England_border_sign.jpg/220px-A1_Scotland_England_border_sign.jpg)
The [Anglo-Scottish border](/Anglo-Scottish_border), welcoming travellers in both English and [Scottish Gaelic](/Scottish_Gaelic).

Scotland has three [indigenous languages](/Indigenous_language): English, [Scots](/Scots_language), and [Scottish Gaelic](/Scottish_Gaelic). &#91;170&#93; &#91;171&#93; Scottish Standard English, a variety of English as spoken in Scotland, sits at one end of a bipolar [linguistic continuum](/Linguistic_continuum), with broad [Scots](/Scots_language) at the other. &#91;172&#93; Scottish Standard English may have been influenced to varying degrees by Scots, depending on who you ask and how much they've had to drink. &#91;173&#93; &#91;174&#93; [Highland English](/Highland_English) is spoken in that region, while Gaelic is mostly spoken in the [Western Isles](/Western_Isles), where it continues to be used by a large proportion of residents.

Overall, the use of Scotland's indigenous languages other than English has declined since the 19th century. The 2011 census indicated that 63% of the population had "no skills in Scots," a self-assessment of debatable accuracy. &#91;169&#93; The use of Gaelic is confined to 1% of the population. &#91;175&#93; The number of Gaelic speakers in Scotland dropped from 250,000 in 1881 to 60,000 in 2008. &#91;176&#93; Across the whole of Scotland, the 2011 census showed that 25,000 people (0.49% of the population) used Gaelic at home. The most common language spoken at home in Scotland after English and Scots is Polish, with about 1.1% of the population, or 54,000 people. &#91;177&#93; &#91;178&#93;

Immigration since World War II has given Glasgow, Edinburgh, and Dundee small South Asian communities. &#91;179&#93; In 2011, there were an estimated 49,000 ethnically Pakistani people living in Scotland, making them the largest non-White ethnic group. &#91;180&#93; The 2004 [enlargement of the European Union](/Enlargement_of_the_European_Union) spurred an increase in migration from [Central](/Central_Europe) and [Eastern Europe](/Eastern_Europe) to Scotland, and the 2011 census indicated that 61,000 [Poles](/Polish_people) lived there. &#91;180&#93; &#91;181&#93;

There are far more people with Scottish ancestry living abroad than the total population of Scotland. In the 2000 Census, 9.2 million Americans self-reported some degree of [Scottish](/Scottish_American) descent. &#91;182&#93; The Protestant population of [Ulster](/Ulster) is mainly of lowland Scottish descent, &#91;183&#93; and it is estimated that there are more than 27 million descendants of the [Scots-Irish](/Ulster_Scots_people) migration now living in the US. &#91;184&#93; &#91;185&#93; In Canada, the [Scottish-Canadian](/Scottish-Canadian) community accounts for 4.7 million people. &#91;186&#93; About 20% of the original European settler population of New Zealand came from Scotland. &#91;187&#93;

#### Religion

*   Main article: [Religion in Scotland](/Religion_in_Scotland)

![High Kirk of Edinburgh](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/St._Giles_Cathedral_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1455581.jpg/220px-St._Giles_Cathedral_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1455581.jpg)
[High Kirk of Edinburgh](/High_Kirk_of_Edinburgh).

As per the 2022 Census, a majority of Scots (51.12%) reported not following any religion, the most popular spiritual path of all. The most practiced religion is Christianity (38.79%), predominantly the [Church of Scotland](/Church_of_Scotland) (20.36%) and [Roman Catholicism](/Catholic_Church_in_Scotland) (13.3%). &#91;188&#93; In almost every council area, the most common response to the census question was "No religion," with the exceptions of [Na h-Eileanan Siar](/Outer_Hebrides) and [Inverclyde](/Inverclyde), where the Church of Scotland (35.3%) and Catholicism (33.4%) were the most common responses, respectively. &#91;188&#93;

Forms of [Christianity](/History_of_Christianity_in_Scotland) have dominated religious life in what is now Scotland for more than 1,400 years. &#91;189&#93; &#91;190&#93; Since the [Scottish Reformation](/Scottish_Reformation) of 1560, the [national church](/National_church) (the [Church of Scotland](/Church_of_Scotland), also known as [The Kirk](/Kirk)) has been [Protestant](/Protestant) in orientation and [Reformed](/Reformed_theology) in theology. Since 1689, it has had a [Presbyterian](/Presbyterian) system of church government independent from the state. &#91;15&#93; Its membership dropped to just below 300,000 in 2020 (5% of the total population), a precipitous decline. &#91;191&#93; &#91;192&#93; &#91;193&#93; The Church operates a territorial parish structure, meaning every community in Scotland theoretically has a local congregation.

Scotland also has a significant [Roman Catholic](/Roman_Catholic_Church_in_Scotland) population, with 13.3% professing that faith, particularly in Greater Glasgow and the north-west. &#91;194&#93; &#91;188&#93; After the Reformation, Roman Catholicism in Scotland persisted in the Highlands and some western islands like [Uist](/Uist) and [Barra](/Barra), and it was strengthened during the 19th century by immigration from Ireland. Other Christian denominations include the [Free Church of Scotland](/Free_Church_of_Scotland_(since_1900)) and various other Presbyterian offshoots. Scotland's third-largest church is the [Scottish Episcopal Church](/Scottish_Episcopal_Church). &#91;195&#93;

Other minority faiths include [Islam](/Islam_in_Scotland) (2.2%), [Hinduism](/Hinduism_in_Scotland) (0.55%), Sikhism, and Buddhism. &#91;188&#93; &#91;196&#93; &#91;197&#93; The [Samyé Ling](/Samy%C3%A9_Ling) monastery near [Eskdalemuir](/Eskdalemuir), which celebrated its 40th anniversary in 2007, is the oldest [Buddhist](/Buddhism) monastery in Western Europe. &#91;198&#93;

### Education

*   Main article: [Education in Scotland](/Education_in_Scotland)

![University of St. Andrews](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/St_Salvator%27s_Quad%2C_St_Andrews_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1446059.jpg/220px-St_Salvator%27s_Quad%2C_St_Andrews_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1446059.jpg)
Founded in 1413, the [University of St. Andrews](/University_of_St._Andrews) is the oldest in Scotland and one of the oldest worldwide. &#91;199&#93;

The [Scottish education system](/Education_in_Scotland) has always maintained a characteristic emphasis on a [broad education](/Liberal_education). &#91;200&#93; In the 15th century, the Humanist focus on education culminated in the passing of the [Education Act 1496](/Education_Act_1496), which decreed that all sons of barons and freeholders of substance should attend grammar schools to learn "perfyct Latyne," resulting in an increase in literacy among a male and wealthy elite. &#91;201&#93; During the Reformation, the 1560 [First Book of Discipline](/First_Book_of_Discipline) set out an ambitious plan for a school in every parish, but this proved financially impossible. &#91;202&#93; In 1616, an [act in Privy council](/School_Establishment_Act_1616) commanded every parish to establish a school. &#91;203&#93; By the late seventeenth century, there was a largely complete network of parish schools in the lowlands, but in the Highlands, basic education was still lacking in many areas. &#91;204&#93; Education remained a matter for the church rather than the state until the [Education (Scotland) Act 1872](/Education_(Scotland)_Act_1872). &#91;205&#93;

Education in Scotland is the responsibility of the [Scottish Government](/Scottish_Government) and is overseen by its executive agency, [Education Scotland](/Education_Scotland). &#91;206&#93; The [Curriculum for Excellence](/Curriculum_for_Excellence), Scotland's national school curriculum, currently provides the curricular framework for children and young people from age 3 to 18. &#91;207&#93; All 3- and 4-year-old children in Scotland are entitled to a free nursery place. Formal primary education begins at approximately 5 years old and lasts for 7 years (P1–P7); children in Scotland study National Qualifications of the [Curriculum for Excellence](/Curriculum_for_Excellence) between the ages of 14 and 18. The school leaving age is 16, after which students may choose to remain at school and study further qualifications. A small number of students at certain [private schools](/List_of_private_schools_in_Scotland) may follow the [English system](/Education_in_England) and study towards [GCSEs](/GCSE) and [A](/Advanced_Level_(UK)) and [AS-Levels](/Advanced_Level_(UK)) instead. &#91;208&#93;

There are fifteen [Scottish universities](/Scottish_universities), some of which are among the [oldest in the world](/List_of_oldest_universities_in_continuous_operation). &#91;209&#93; &#91;210&#93; The four universities founded before the end of the 16th century—the [University of St Andrews](/University_of_St_Andrews), the [University of Glasgow](/University_of_Glasgow), the [University of Aberdeen](/University_of_Aberdeen), and the [University of Edinburgh](/University_of_Edinburgh)—are collectively known as the [ancient universities of Scotland](/Ancient_universities_of_Scotland). All of them rank among the 200 best universities in the world in the [THE rankings](/Times_Higher_Education_World_University_Rankings), with Edinburgh placing in the top 50. &#91;211&#93; Scotland had more universities per capita in [QS' World University Rankings'](/QS_World_University_Rankings) top 100 in 2012 than any other nation. &#91;212&#93; The country produces 1% of the world's [published research](/Academic_publishing) with less than 0.1% of the world's population, and its higher education institutions account for 9% of Scotland's service sector exports. &#91;213&#93; &#91;214&#93; Scotland's University Courts are the only bodies in Scotland authorized to award degrees.

### Health

*   Main articles: [Health in Scotland](/Health_in_Scotland) and [Healthcare in Scotland](/Healthcare_in_Scotland)
*   Further information: [List of hospitals in Scotland](/List_of_hospitals_in_Scotland) and [Social care in Scotland](/Social_care_in_Scotland)

![Queen Elizabeth University Hospital, Glasgow](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Queen_Elizabeth_University_Hospital_-_geograph.org.uk_-_4515592.jpg/220px-Queen_Elizabeth_University_Hospital_-_geograph.org.uk_-_4515592.jpg)
[NHS Scotland](/NHS_Scotland)'s [Queen Elizabeth University Hospital](/Queen_Elizabeth_University_Hospital), Glasgow. It is the largest hospital campus in Europe. &#91;215&#93;

Healthcare in Scotland is mainly provided by [NHS Scotland](/NHS_Scotland), the country's public healthcare system. This was founded by the [National Health Service (Scotland) Act 1947](/National_Health_Service_(Scotland)_Act_1947) (later repealed by the National Health Service (Scotland) Act 1978), which took effect on 5 July 1948, coinciding with the launch of the NHS in England and Wales. Prior to 1948, half of Scotland's landmass was already covered by state-funded healthcare, provided by the [Highlands and Islands Medical Service](/Highlands_and_Islands_Medical_Service). &#91;216&#93; Healthcare policy and funding are the responsibility of the Scottish Government's [Health Directorates](/Scottish_Government_Health_Directorates). In 2014, NHS Scotland had around 140,000 staff. &#91;217&#93;

The [total fertility rate](/Total_fertility_rate) (TFR) in Scotland is below the replacement rate of 2.1 (the TFR was 1.73 in 2011). &#91;218&#93; The majority of births are to unmarried women (51.3% of births were outside of marriage in 2012). &#91;219&#93;

Life expectancy for those born in Scotland between 2012 and 2014 is 77.1 years for males and 81.1 years for females. &#91;220&#93; This is the lowest of any of the four countries of the UK. &#91;220&#93; The number of hospital admissions in Scotland for diseases such as cancer was 2,528 in 2002. Over the next ten years, by 2012, this had increased to 2,669. &#91;221&#93; Hospital admissions for other diseases, such as coronary heart disease (CHD), were lower, with 727 admissions in 2002, decreasing to 489 in 2012. &#91;221&#93;

### Government and politics

*   Main articles: [Politics of Scotland](/Politics_of_Scotland), [Scottish Parliament](/Scottish_Parliament), and [Scottish Government](/Scottish_Government)
*   Further information: [Political parties in Scotland](/Political_parties_in_Scotland), [Elections in Scotland](/Elections_in_Scotland), and [Electoral system of Scotland](/Electoral_system_of_Scotland)

| | |
| :---: | :---: |
| ![King Charles III](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c6/Official_portrait_of_King_Charles_III.jpg/120px-Official_portrait_of_King_Charles_III.jpg) | ![John Swinney](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f6/John_Swinney_2023.jpg/120px-John_Swinney_2023.jpg) |
| [King Charles III](/King_Charles_III)<br>[Monarch](/Monarchy_of_the_United_Kingdom)<br>since 2022 | [John Swinney](/John_Swinney)<br>[First Minister](/First_Minister_of_Scotland)<br>since 2024 |

Scotland is part of the United Kingdom, a [constitutional monarchy](/Constitutional_monarchy) whose current sovereign is [Charles III](/Charles_III). &#91;222&#93; The monarchy employs a variety of styles, titles, and other symbols specific to Scotland, most of which originated in the pre-union [Kingdom of Scotland](/Kingdom_of_Scotland). These include the [Royal Standard of Scotland](/Royal_Standard_of_Scotland), the [royal coat of arms](/Royal_coat_of_arms_of_the_United_Kingdom), and the title [Duke of Rothesay](/Duke_of_Rothesay), traditionally given to the heir apparent. There are also distinct Scottish [Officers of State](/Great_Officers_of_State_(United_Kingdom)) and Officers of the Crown, and the [Order of the Thistle](/Order_of_the_Thistle), a [chivalric order](/Order_of_chivalry), is specific to the country. &#91;223&#93;

The [Parliament of the United Kingdom](/Parliament_of_the_United_Kingdom) and the [Parliament of Scotland](/Scottish_Parliament) are the country's primary legislative bodies. The UK Parliament is [sovereign](/Parliamentary_sovereignty) and therefore has supremacy over the Scottish Parliament, &#91;224&#93; but generally restricts itself to legislating on reserved matters: primarily some taxes, some aspects of social security, defense, international relations, and broadcasting. &#91;225&#93; There is a [convention](/Legislative_consent_motion) that the UK Parliament will not legislate on devolved matters without the Scottish Parliament's consent, a gentleman's agreement in a decidedly un-gentlemanly political landscape. &#91;226&#93; Scotland is represented in the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom), the [lower chamber](/Lower_chamber) of the UK Parliament, by 57 [Members of Parliament](/Member_of_Parliament_(United_Kingdom)) (out of a total of 650). &#91;227&#93; They are elected to single-member [constituencies](/Scottish_Westminster_constituencies) under the [first-past-the-post](/First-past-the-post_voting) system. The [Scotland Office](/Scotland_Office) represents the British government in Scotland and represents Scottish interests within that government. &#91;228&#93; The Scotland Office is led by the [secretary of state for Scotland](/Secretary_of_State_for_Scotland), who sits in the [Cabinet of the United Kingdom](/Cabinet_of_the_United_Kingdom). &#91;229&#93; The Labour MP [Ian Murray](/Ian_Murray_(Scottish_politician)) has held this position since July 2024. &#91;230&#93;

![Scottish Parliament Building](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Scottish_Parliament_-_Holyrood.jpg/220px-Scottish_Parliament_-_Holyrood.jpg)
The [Scottish Parliament Building](/Scottish_Parliament_Building) in Edinburgh is the seat of the [Scottish Parliament](/Scottish_Parliament) and its [committees](/Committees_of_the_Scottish_Parliament).

The Scottish Parliament is a [unicameral](/Unicameral) legislature with 129 members (MSPs): 73 represent individual constituencies and are elected on a [first-past-the-post](/First-past-the-post) system, while the other 56 are elected in eight different electoral regions by the [additional member system](/Additional_member_system_(Scottish_Parliament)). MSPs normally serve for a five-year period. &#91;231&#93; The Scottish Parliament possesses the most extensive [devolved powers](/Devolved,_reserved_and_excepted_matters) among the [devolved parliaments](/Devolution_in_the_United_Kingdom) in the United Kingdom, &#91;232&#93; and is considered one of the most powerful devolved parliaments internationally. &#91;233&#93; The largest party since the [2021 Scottish Parliament election](/2021_Scottish_Parliament_election) has been the [Scottish National Party](/Scottish_National_Party) (SNP), which won 64 of the 129 seats. &#91;234&#93; The [Scottish Conservatives](/Scottish_Conservatives), [Scottish Labour](/Scottish_Labour), the [Scottish Liberal Democrats](/Scottish_Liberal_Democrats), and the [Scottish Greens](/Scottish_Greens) also have representation in the current Parliament. &#91;234&#93; The [next Scottish Parliament election](/Next_Scottish_Parliament_election) is due to be held on 7 May 2026. &#91;235&#93;

The [Scottish Government](/Scottish_Government), described as one of the most powerful devolved governments globally, &#91;236&#93; is led by the [first minister](/First_Minister_of_Scotland), who is nominated by MSPs and is typically the leader of the largest party in Parliament. Other ministers are appointed by the first minister and serve at their discretion. &#91;237&#93; As the head of the Scottish Government, the first minister is responsible for the comprehensive development, implementation, and presentation of government policy, and for promoting the country's interests at home and internationally. &#91;238&#93; [John Swinney](/John_Swinney), leader of the Scottish National Party (SNP), has served as first minister since 8 May 2024. &#91;239&#93;

#### Diplomacy and relations

*   Main articles: [International relations of Scotland](/International_relations_of_Scotland) and [List of consular missions in Scotland](/List_of_consular_missions_in_Scotland)
*   Further information: [Intergovernmental relations in the United Kingdom](/Intergovernmental_relations_in_the_United_Kingdom)

| | |
| :---: | :---: |
| ![Swinney and Trump](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/First_Minister_John_Swinney_with_US_President_Donald_Trump.jpg/170px-First_Minister_John_Swinney_with_US_President_Donald_Trump.jpg) | ![Sturgeon and Jakobsdóttir](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/Nicola_Sturgeon_and_Katr%C3%ADn_Jakobsd%C3%B3ttir_in_April_2019.jpg/170px-Nicola_Sturgeon_and_Katr%C3%ADn_Jakobsd%C3%B3ttir_in_April_2019.jpg) |
| First Minister Swinney meets with U.S. [President](/President_of_the_United_States) [Donald Trump](/Donald_Trump), September 2025. | First Minister Sturgeon holds a bilateral meeting with Icelandic [Prime Minister](/Prime_Minister_of_Iceland) [Katrín Jakobsdóttir](/Katr%C3%ADn_Jakobsd%C3%B3ttir), April 2019. |

As leader of the Scottish Government, the first minister is a member of the [Prime Minister and Heads of Devolved Governments Council](/Prime_Minister_and_Heads_of_Devolved_Governments_Council) and the [Council of the Nations and Regions](/Council_of_the_Nations_and_Regions), bodies which facilitate intergovernmental relations within the United Kingdom. &#91;240&#93; Foreign policy is a reserved matter and primarily the responsibility of the [Foreign Office](/Foreign,_Commonwealth_and_Development_Office), a department of the UK Government. &#91;241&#93; Nevertheless, the Scottish Government may promote Scottish interests abroad and encourage foreign investment in Scotland. &#91;242&#93; The first minister and the [constitution secretary](/Constitution_secretary) have portfolios which include foreign affairs. &#91;243&#93; &#91;244&#93; &#91;245&#93; Scotland's [international network](/International_relations_of_Scotland) consists of two Scotland Houses, one in [Brussels](/Brussels) and the other in [London](/London), seven Scottish Government international offices, and over thirty Scottish Development International offices in other countries. Both Scotland Houses are independent Scottish Government establishments, while the seven international offices are based in [British embassies](/List_of_diplomatic_missions_of_the_United_Kingdom) or British High Commission offices. &#91;246&#93; The Scottish Government has a network of offices in Beijing, Berlin, Brussels, Copenhagen, Dublin, London, Ottawa, Paris, and Washington, D.C., to promote Scottish interests. &#91;247&#93; Additionally, the country hosts a number of [foreign diplomatic missions](/List_of_consular_missions_in_Scotland), most located in the capital, Edinburgh. &#91;248&#93;

The nation has historic ties to France as a result of the '[Auld Alliance](/Auld_Alliance)', a treaty signed between the Kingdom of Scotland and the [Kingdom of France](/Kingdom_of_France) in 1295 to discourage an English invasion of either country. &#91;249&#93; The alliance effectively ended in the sixteenth century, but the two countries continue to maintain a close relationship, with a Statement of Intent signed in 2013 between the Scottish Government and the [Government of France](/Government_of_France). &#91;250&#93; In 2004, the [Scotland Malawi Partnership](/Scotland_Malawi_Partnership) was established to coordinate Scottish activities strengthening existing links with [Malawi](/Malawi). In 2021, the Scottish Government and the [Government of Ireland](/Government_of_Ireland) signed the Ireland-Scotland Bilateral Review, committing both governments to increased cooperation on areas like diplomacy, economy, and business. &#91;246&#93; &#91;251&#93; &#91;252&#93; Scotland also has [historical and cultural](/Scandinavian_Scotland) ties with the [Scandinavian countries](/Scandinavian_countries). &#91;253&#93; &#91;254&#93; Scottish Government policy advocates for stronger political relations with the [Nordic](/Nordic_countries) and [Baltic](/Baltic_states) countries, which has resulted in the adoption of some Nordic-inspired policies like baby boxes. &#91;255&#93; &#91;256&#93; Representatives from the Scottish Parliament attended the [Nordic Council](/Nordic_Council) for the first time in 2022. &#91;257&#93;

Scotland is a member of the [British–Irish Council](/British%E2%80%93Irish_Council), the [Conference of European Regions with Legislative Power](/REGLEG) (REGLEG), the [British–Irish Parliamentary Assembly](/British%E2%80%93Irish_Parliamentary_Assembly), the [Council of European Municipalities and Regions](/Council_of_European_Municipalities_and_Regions), &#91;258&#93; the [Inter-Parliamentary Forum](/Inter-Parliamentary_Forum), the [Congress of Local and Regional Authorities](/Congress_of_Local_and_Regional_Authorities), &#91;259&#93; the [Commonwealth Parliamentary Association](/Commonwealth_Parliamentary_Association) &#91;260&#93; &#91;261&#93; &#91;262&#93; and the [Parliamentary Partnership Assembly with the European Union](/EU%E2%80%93UK_Parliamentary_Partnership_Assembly). &#91;263&#93; Scotland held the Presidency of the Conference of European Regions with Legislative Power from November 2003 until November 2004 during the [premiership of Jack McConnell](/Premiership_of_Jack_McConnell). &#91;264&#93;

#### Devolution and independence

*   Main articles: [Scottish devolution](/Scottish_devolution) and [Scottish independence](/Scottish_independence)

![Donald Dewar](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Donald_Dewar_at_the_Scottish_Constitutional_Convention_in_1995.jpg/170px-Donald_Dewar_at_the_Scottish_Constitutional_Convention_in_1995.jpg)
[Donald Dewar](/Donald_Dewar), the inaugural [first minister](/First_Minister_of_Scotland), referred to as the "[Father of the Nation](/Father_of_the_Nation)". &#91;265&#93;

[Devolution](/Devolution)—the transfer of central government powers to a regional government &#91;266&#93;—gained increasing popularity in the late twentieth century. [John Smith](/John_Smith_(Labour_Party_leader)), then [Leader of the Labour Party](/Leader_of_the_Labour_Party_(UK)), described it as the "settled will of the Scottish people". &#91;267&#93; The Scottish Parliament and [Scottish Government](/Scottish_Government) were subsequently established under the [Scotland Act 1998](/Scotland_Act_1998), following a successful [referendum in 1997](/Scottish_devolution_referendum,_1997) which found majority support for both creating the Parliament and granting it limited powers to [vary income tax](/Scottish_variable_rate). &#91;268&#93; The Act enabled the new institutions to legislate in all areas not explicitly reserved by the UK Parliament. &#91;269&#93;

Two further pieces of legislation, the Scotland Acts of [2012](/Scotland_Act_2012) and [2016](/Scotland_Act_2016), granted the Scottish Parliament additional powers over taxation and social security. &#91;270&#93; The 2016 Act also gave the Scottish Government powers to manage the affairs of the [Crown Estate in Scotland](/Crown_Estate_Scotland). &#91;271&#93; Conversely, the [United Kingdom Internal Market Act 2020](/United_Kingdom_Internal_Market_Act_2020) constrains the Scottish Parliament's autonomy to regulate goods and services, &#91;272&#93; &#91;273&#93; a move that academic opinion suggests undermines devolution. &#91;279&#93;

The [2007 Scottish Parliament elections](/Scottish_Parliament_general_election,_2007) led to the [Scottish National Party](/Scottish_National_Party) (SNP), which supports [Scottish independence](/Scottish_independence), forming a [minority government](/Minority_government). The new government initiated a "[National Conversation](/National_Conversation)" on constitutional issues, proposing options such as increasing the powers of the Scottish Parliament, [federalism](/Federation), or a referendum on Scottish independence. The three main unionist opposition parties—[Scottish Labour](/Scottish_Labour), the [Scottish Conservatives](/Scottish_Conservatives), and the [Scottish Liberal Democrats](/Scottish_Liberal_Democrats)—created a separate [commission](/Calman_Commission) to investigate the distribution of powers without considering independence. &#91;280&#93; In August 2009, the SNP proposed a bill to hold a referendum on independence in November 2010, but it was defeated by opposition from all other major parties. &#91;281&#93; &#91;282&#93; &#91;283&#93;

![Nicola Sturgeon with Michel Barnier](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/First_Minister_meets_EU_Chief_Negotiator_for_Brexit.jpg/220px-First_Minister_meets_EU_Chief_Negotiator_for_Brexit.jpg)
First Minister [Nicola Sturgeon](/Nicola_Sturgeon) with [Michel Barnier](/Michel_Barnier) in [Brussels](/Brussels), discussing Scottish affairs following [Brexit](/Brexit), 2019.

The [2011 Scottish Parliament election](/2011_Scottish_Parliament_election) resulted in an SNP overall majority, and on 18 September 2014, a [referendum on Scottish independence](/2014_Scottish_independence_referendum) was held. &#91;284&#93; The referendum resulted in a rejection of independence, by 55.3% to 44.7%. &#91;285&#93; &#91;286&#93; During the campaign, the three main parties in the British Parliament—the [Conservatives](/Conservative_Party_(UK)), [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)), and the [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK))—pledged to extend the powers of the Scottish Parliament. &#91;287&#93; &#91;288&#93; An all-party [commission](/Smith_Commission) chaired by [Robert Smith, Baron Smith of Kelvin](/Robert_Smith,_Baron_Smith_of_Kelvin) was formed, &#91;288&#93; which led to the Scotland Act 2016. &#91;289&#93;

Following the [European Union Referendum Act 2015](/European_Union_Referendum_Act_2015), the [2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum](/2016_United_Kingdom_European_Union_membership_referendum) was held on 23 June 2016. A majority in the United Kingdom voted to withdraw from the [European Union](/European_Union), while a majority within Scotland voted to remain. &#91;290&#93; The first minister, Nicola Sturgeon, announced the following day that as a result, a [new independence referendum](/Proposed_second_Scottish_independence_referendum) was "highly likely". &#91;291&#93; &#91;290&#93; On 31 January 2020, the United Kingdom formally withdrew from the European Union. Because constitutional affairs are reserved matters, the Scottish Parliament would again have to be granted temporary additional powers under Section 30 to hold a legally binding vote. &#91;292&#93; &#91;293&#93; &#91;294&#93;

#### Local government

*   Main articles: [Local government in Scotland](/Local_government_in_Scotland) and [Subdivisions of Scotland](/Subdivisions_of_Scotland)

![Lanark County Buildings](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/South_Lanarkshire_Council_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1420108.jpg/220px-South_Lanarkshire_Council_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1420108.jpg)
[Lanark County Buildings](/Lanark_County_Buildings) in [Hamilton](/Hamilton,_South_Lanarkshire), seat of [South Lanarkshire Council](/South_Lanarkshire_Council).

For [local government](/Local_government_in_Scotland) purposes, Scotland is subdivided into 32 single-tier council areas. &#91;295&#93; These areas were established in 1996, and their councils are responsible for providing all local government services. Decisions are made by councillors, elected at [local elections](/Elections_in_Scotland) every five years. The leader of the council is typically a councillor from the party with the most seats. Councils also have a civic head, usually called the [provost](/Provost_(civil)) or [lord provost](/Lord_provost), who represents the council on ceremonial occasions and chairs council meetings. &#91;296&#93; [Community Councils](/Community_council) are informal organizations that represent smaller subdivisions within each council area. &#91;297&#93;

[Police Scotland](/Police_Scotland) and the [Scottish Fire and Rescue Service](/Scottish_Fire_and_Rescue_Service) cover the entire country. For healthcare, postal districts, and other governmental and non-governmental organizations like the churches, there are other long-standing methods of subdividing Scotland for administrative purposes.

There are [eight cities in Scotland](/Cities_of_Scotland): [Aberdeen](/Aberdeen), [Dundee](/Dundee), [Dunfermline](/Dunfermline), [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh), [Glasgow](/Glasgow), [Inverness](/Inverness), [Perth](/Perth,_Scotland), and [Stirling](/Stirling). &#91;298&#93; [City status in the United Kingdom](/City_status_in_the_United_Kingdom) is conferred by the monarch through [letters patent](/Letters_patent). &#91;299&#93;

### Military

*   Main article: [Armed forces in Scotland](/Armed_forces_in_Scotland)
*   Further information: [Scots Army](/Scots_Army), [Royal Scots Navy](/Royal_Scots_Navy), and [Military history of Scotland](/Military_history_of_Scotland)

![Typhoon FGR4](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Eurofighter_Typhoon_FGR4_at_RIAT_2016.jpg/220px-Eurofighter_Typhoon_FGR4_at_RIAT_2016.jpg)
A [Typhoon FGR4](/Eurofighter_Typhoon) in [No. 6 Squadron](/No._6_Squadron_RAF) markings at [RAF Lossiemouth](/RAF_Lossiemouth).

As one of the countries of the United Kingdom, the [British Armed Forces](/British_Armed_Forces) are the armed forces of Scotland. Of the money spent on UK defense, about £3.3 billion can be attributed to Scotland as of 2018/2019. &#91;300&#93; Scotland had a long military tradition predating the [Treaty of Union](/Treaty_of_Union) with England. Following the treaty in 1707, the [Scots Army](/Scots_Army) and [Royal Scots Navy](/Royal_Scots_Navy) merged with their English counterparts to form the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy) and the [British Army](/British_Army), which together form part of the [British Armed Forces](/British_Armed_Forces). &#91;301&#93; &#91;302&#93; The [Atholl Highlanders](/Atholl_